			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If I were able to cast blame for the majority of cases mentioned here, I would put it on DAoC programming or design staff.  There just is no reason I can think of to have experience loss in many of these situations.  The first mentioned, in particular, the player had already killed the environmental monster before being killed by the other realm's players.  You should just not lose experience in this situation.  If the mob isn't dead yet, or the mob kills you, particularly the latter then it would be hard to determine whether you should would have killed it or not had the other realm not intervened and losing exp doesn't seem so ridiculous.
<br />

<br />
It does seem to me the role we are playing in RvR is hatred of the other side, so it doesn't seem so infantile to attack whenever you see an enemy, even in DF.  Of course I would never have guessed that attacking an enemy who had taken some damage from a mob would cause them to lose exp.  My own experience of RvR has only been in the Battlegrounds, where attacks are over so quickly that you hardly have time to check if someone is by themselves or significantly weaker than you.
<br />

<br />
How does the game know when you are no longer subject to exp loss.  When you are fully healed?  After a timer has expired?  Seems to me it would be much fairer to take exp away only if killed by a mob and never when killed by another realm player.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
